{
  "texts": [
    "Since apart from recent historical times, human ancestors did not shower or bathe for millions of years, the strength of hominin body odor becomes more overpowering.",
    "In this connection, I suggest that the patches of hair in armpits and groin were developed primarily for their hyper-effective smell-producing ability.",
    "Alternative suggestions for underarm hair (e.g., Kohl and Francoeur, 2002; Hofer et al., 2018; see also Wedekind, 2007) as a sexual attraction tool, or as a friction-reducing tool do not seem very convincing, as most humans now diligently try to get rid of body odor, particularly when meeting the opposite sex, and humans who shave their armpits (including sportsmen) never report any complications from injuries.",
    "I would predict, that aposematic species in general would have more smellproducing glands.",
    "Evening concerts Kortlandt (1973) made a brilliant (and mostly neglected) suggestion that one way to secure nocturnal sleep was to organize loud evening \"concerts\" to scare away potential predators, citing the behavior of chimpanzee groups who sometimes produce loud concerts before they sleep, and also the behavior of African tribes living in the forests, who organize the same kind of loud evening displays."
  ]
}